EAIF anchored the successful bond issuance of Helios Towers Africa. The capital will be used for the expansion of its telecom tower business in Africa.

EAIF invested XOF15 billion in a bond issue that raised XOF100 billion (ca. US$170 million) for investment in the Senegal business of Sonatel S.A, a West African telecommunications company. Sonatel will use the bond proceeds to extend and enlarge its 4G + network in urban and rural areas and renew and upgrade service platforms. Sonatel is investing in new activities such as energy, banking and multimedia content, which will benefit from the bond fundraising.
Development of approximately 80 rooftop solar projects on net-metering concept and supply electricity to commercial and residential customers.

EAIF is lending the Guinea Alumina Corporation (GAC) US$40 million as part of a US$750 million for the development of a Bauxite mine. EAIF's capital will be used to finance port and marine facilities, the railway and associated infrastructure.

EAIF is lending US$30 million to Kenmare Resources plc as part of the financing of a US$145 million expansion at the company’s Moma Mine, on the north east coast of Mozambique. The EAIF loan is designated to meet the cost of the new infrastructure needed to move heavy equipment and provide electricity at the company’s new location. The local economy to benefit from new road, causeway and energy infrastructure.

EAIF invested XOF* 8.3 billion (cUS$15 million) in a local currency capital market bond issue by Senegal’s Port Autonome de Dakar (PAD), the owner of the Port of Dakar.  The bond raised over XOF60 billion (US$107million).  The issue marks the start of the process of relocating the capital city’s port and its operations to a new greenfield site. The proceeds of the PAD bond will help fund phases one, two and three of the move of the port of Dakar from the centre of the city to a deep water port location 35 km by sea and 70 km by road from the existing site. The port will be part of the new special economic zone that includes Dakar’s international airport, which opened in 2017. New and upgraded road and rail links will connect the port and airport to Dakar and into the regional transport network.
